05307nam a22008895i 9780674736023DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013957072  a(OCoLC)1029827755  a(OCoLC)1032692926  a(OCoLC)1037982434  a(OCoLC)1041991117  a(OCoLC)1046612010  a(OCoLC)1046995448  a(OCoLC)979910259  a97806747360237 a10.4159/harvard.97806747360232doi  a(DE-B1597)427416  a(OCoLC)891397670  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a324.2732231 aMuirhead, Russell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Promise of Party in a Polarized Age /cRussell Muirhead. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- t1. THE PARTY PROBLEM -- t2. The Partisan Threat -- t3. The Partisan Community -- t4. Reasonable Partisans -- t5. Loyal Partisans -- t6. The Primary Problem -- t7. Partisanship at Home: The Legislature -- t8. Partisanship beyond the Legislature -- t9. Can the Government Govern? -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the root of America’s broken politics is hyperbolic partisanship. It distorts perceptions, inflames disagreements, and poisons the democratic process. Citizens pine for a time when liberals and conservatives compromised with one another—or they yearn for a post-partisan future when the common good trumps ideology and self-interest. Russell Muirhead argues that better partisanship, not less partisanship, is the solution to America’s political predicament. Instead of striving to overcome our differences, we should learn how to engage them. The political conflicts that provide fodder for cable news shows are not simply manufactured from thin air. However sensationalized they become in the retelling, they originate in authentic disagreements over what constitutes the common welfare. Republicans vest responsibility in each citizen for dealing with bad decisions and bad luck, and want every individual and family to enjoy the benefits of good decisions and good luck. Democrats ask citizens to stand together to insure one another against the worst consequences of misfortune or poor judgment, and especially to insure children against some of the consequences of their parents’ bad decisions or lack of opportunities. These are fundamental differences that fantasies of bipartisan consensus cannot dissolve. Disagreement without parties is disempowering, Muirhead says. The remedy is not for citizens and elected officials to learn to “just get along” but for them to bring a skeptical sensibility even to their own convictions, and to learn to disagree as partisans and govern through compromise despite those disagreements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDivided governmentxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aDivided governmentzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturexUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical partiesxUnited States. 0aPolitical partieszUnited States. 0aTwo-party systemsxUnited States. 0aTwo-party systemszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2014z9783110370416oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473602340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674736023423Coveruhttps://www.d